-- в”Ђв”Ђ MkDocs в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$MkDocs is a free, open-source static site generator written in Python that turns Markdown files into fast, searchable documentation websites configured with a single YAML file.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$MkDocs Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$MkDocs review: free open-source Python documentation site generator, features, pricing (free), setup, and alternatives compared for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$MkDocs is a free, open-source static site generator built in Python and designed specifically for project documentation. It converts a directory of Markdown files into a complete static HTML website, configured through a single mkdocs.yml YAML file that controls navigation, theme, and plugins. The first tagged release, version 0.2, shipped in January 2014, created by developer Tom Christie, also known for creating Django REST Framework. MkDocs has no company behind it; it is maintained as a community open-source project under a permissive license on GitHub, with maintainership having changed hands among community contributors over the years. As of 2026, the project's original creator has returned to lead maintenance and announced that a new major version, MkDocs 2.0, is in development.

Architecturally, MkDocs ships with a built-in development server that live-reloads pages as documentation is edited, and it builds fully static HTML, CSS, and JS output that can be hosted anywhere, including GitHub Pages, Read the Docs, Netlify, or Amazon S3, with no server-side runtime required. It includes two built-in themes, the default mkdocs theme and a readthedocs theme, and supports third-party themes, the most popular of which is Material for MkDocs, a separate and more feature-rich theme project built on top of MkDocs. MkDocs supports a plugin architecture, enabled via the plugins key in mkdocs.yml, that lets developers extend the build process, and it ships a built-in search plugin that generates a client-side search index so documentation sites are searchable without any backend. Core features include Markdown-to-HTML conversion via Python-Markdown and its extensions, such as tables, fenced code blocks, and admonitions, configurable navigation trees, versioning support often paired with the separate mike tool, and straightforward continuous deployment via the mkdocs gh-deploy command or CI pipelines.

Because MkDocs is fully open source, it has no pricing plans, no paid tiers, and no commercial edition; the tool itself is entirely free under a permissive license, and any hosting costs come from wherever the static site is deployed, not from MkDocs itself. Its target audience is developers, open-source maintainers, and technical writers who want lightweight, Git-friendly documentation authored in Markdown rather than heavier CMS-based tools. It is used by major organizations and open-source projects alike; companies such as Atlassian, Google, Microsoft, and Red Hat, and projects like Kubernetes, Electron, and WebKit have used MkDocs, frequently via the Material for MkDocs theme, for their documentation sites. MkDocs's main alternatives include Sphinx, also Python-based but reStructuredText-oriented and more feature-heavy, Docusaurus (a React-based generator by Meta), GitBook (a hosted, commercial platform), Jekyll, Hugo, and VuePress or VitePress. MkDocs differentiates itself with an especially simple, low-configuration setup, tight Markdown-first authoring, and a lightweight core that plugins and themes, especially Material for MkDocs, can extend for more advanced documentation needs.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1bde5f50-16ca-4a06-bfe7-446daf35604f';

