-- в”Ђв”Ђ MLflow в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$MLflow is an open-source platform for managing the machine learning and generative AI lifecycle, covering experiment tracking, model packaging, a model registry, evaluation, and deployment.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source (with managed offerings from cloud vendors)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted); managed MLflow billed as part of platform usage, e.g. Databricks$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA (Databricks, original creator)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$MLflow Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$MLflow review: open-source ML and LLM lifecycle platform features, pricing, model registry, tracking, and top alternatives compared for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$MLflow is an open-source platform for managing the complete machine learning and, more recently, generative AI and agent lifecycle: experiment tracking, model packaging, a model registry, evaluation, and deployment. It was created by engineers at Databricks and first released in June 2018, growing out of the experience of Matei Zaharia, creator of Apache Spark and a Databricks co-founder, who observed that organizations repeatedly struggled to track experiments, reproduce results, and move models from notebooks into production in a structured, tool-agnostic way. Databricks, founded in 2013 and headquartered in San Francisco, built MLflow with an explicitly open design: it works with any ML library, algorithm, or language through simple REST APIs and file formats rather than being tied to Databricks' own platform. MLflow was later donated to the Linux Foundation, which now stewards its open governance, and the project has grown to more than 30 million monthly downloads with thousands of organizations using it in production.

MLflow is organized around four core components. MLflow Tracking logs parameters, metrics, code versions, and output artifacts from ML experiments so runs can be compared and reproduced. MLflow Projects packages ML code in a reusable, reproducible format with a defined environment and entry points so it can run consistently across platforms. MLflow Models provides a standard packaging format for models from libraries like scikit-learn, PyTorch, TensorFlow, and XGBoost so they can be deployed to many serving environments without rewriting code. MLflow Model Registry adds a centralized store with a UI and API for versioning models, adding descriptions and tags, and moving models through stages such as Staging and Production, with full lineage back to the run that produced them. Since MLflow 2.x and 3.0, the project has expanded significantly into generative AI: LLM and agent tracing, prompt management, evaluation harnesses for LLM outputs, and an AI Gateway for managing access and cost across model providers.

Because MLflow is fully open source under the Apache 2.0 license, the core software has no license fee and can be self-hosted for free on a laptop, on-prem server, or any cloud. Organizations that don't want to operate their own MLflow tracking server can instead use managed or hosted MLflow offered by cloud vendors, most notably Databricks' Managed MLflow, which integrates with Unity Catalog and Databricks' Data Intelligence Platform and is billed as part of Databricks platform usage rather than as a separate MLflow subscription; AWS SageMaker and Azure Databricks also offer managed MLflow tracking. MLflow's target audience spans individual data scientists, ML platform teams, and enterprises building production ML and AI systems who need vendor-neutral experiment tracking and model governance. Its main competitors and alternatives include Weights and Biases, a polished hosted experiment tracking and collaboration platform billed per seat, Kubeflow, a Kubernetes-native orchestration platform for training and serving that occupies a different layer of the stack, Neptune.ai, and ZenML. MLflow differentiates itself by being free, open source, framework-agnostic, and self-hostable, while still covering the full lifecycle from tracking through registry to deployment and, increasingly, LLM and agent observability.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '731c611d-030c-488a-b3cb-8255aa73e8ab';

